  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Dog Rapid
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At first dawn I depart from Dragon Harbor,
    By twilight I moor at the Dog Rapid.
    Cunning clouds mock the setting sun,
    While jagged stones resist the raging current.

    In water-lands, autumn arrives early with its chill,
    The boat pavilion grows even colder through the night.
    These river mountains surpass any painting—
    Do not mistake them for mere brush and ink.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Dragon Harbor (龍浦) and the Dog Rapid (犬灘) are actual landmarks on a Korean river journey, likely the Han River or Yeongsan River. ''Water-lands'' refers to regions characterized by rivers and wetlands. The final couplet presents a classical paradox: that living nature surpasses artistic representation, yet the poem itself immortalizes the landscape through verse.'
